xtual, theoretical, historical, and material approaches. The result is a comprehensive collection of essays that illuminates Chaucer's aesthetics, philosophical complexity, and continued relevance. Part innovative scholarship, part how-to manual, the volume includes apparatus to help less experienced readers of Chaucer negotiate its contents. In addition to fourteen main essays, the volume also includes three response essays, each modelling how a seasoned scholar uses the chapters to develop his or her own thinking about Chaucer. Thus, the companion offers something to audiences of all levels who wish to read, research, and enjoy Chaucer, his language, and his works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCanterbury Tales.  aChaucer.  alanguage.  aliterary criticism.  amedieval.  amiddle English.1 aBarr, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrington, Candace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatkie, Stephanie L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBatkie, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurger, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterfield, Ardis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCannon, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrocker, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinshaw, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodden, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v